  <!-- Intro -->
  <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mb-6">RCF and RPM are standard terms in the context of centrifuges. This article explains the difference between the two terms and why RCF is more relevant to centrifuges. Though the two terms are related mathematically, they are vastly different from the application's perspective.</p>

  <!-- What is RCF -->
  <h2 id="what-is-rcf" class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold font-heading text-navy mb-4">What is RCF?</h2>
  <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mb-6">RCF stands for <strong>Relative Centrifugal Force</strong>. The force experienced by any mass (solid, liquid, or gaseous) that rotates around a fixed axis is known as the centrifugal force. RCF is this centrifugal force expressed in terms of gravity. In other words, RCF is the centrifugal force ratio to gravitational force. Therefore it is also referred to as g-force.</p>

  <!-- What is RPM -->
  <h2 id="what-is-rpm" class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold font-heading text-navy mb-4">What is RPM?</h2>
  <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mb-6">RPM is the abbreviation for <strong>Revolutions Per Minute</strong>. It is a measure of the speed of rotation of any object. In a centrifuge, the RPM indicates the number of rotations the centrifuge bowl completes in one minute. RPM is a unitless number independent of any object's properties.</p>

  <!-- Difference Between RCF and RPM -->
  <h2 id="difference-rcf-rpm" class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold font-heading text-navy mb-4">Difference Between RCF and RPM</h2>
  <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Though RCF and RPM are units of measurement related to centrifuges, they are fundamentally different. The RCF of a centrifuge is the actual centrifugal force (or g-force) generated by the centrifuge bowl rotation.</p>
  <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mb-6">While the RPM is the speed of rotation of the bowl, the RCF functions as the RPM and the rotating object's radius.</p>

  <!-- Why use RCF and not RPM -->
  <h2 id="why-rcf-not-rpm" class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold font-heading text-navy mb-4">Why use RCF and not RPM?</h2>
  <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mb-4">As explained above, the RCF measures the centrifugal force generated by the centrifuge. This force (g-force) is directly related to the efficiency of the centrifuge. This is because the RCF indicates the centrifuge force exerted, which defines the centrifuge's <a href="/disc-stack-centrifuge-efficiency/" class="text-navy font-semibold hover:text-gold transition-colors">separation efficiency</a>.</p>
  <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mb-6">The centrifuge RPM merely indicates the bowl speed but does not define the centrifugal force. In conjunction with the RPM, the rotation radius determines the centrifugal force shown by the RCF formula below.</p>

  <!-- Example of RPM vs. RCF -->
  <h2 id="example-rcf-rpm" class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold font-heading text-navy mb-4">Example of RPM vs. RCF in a Centrifuge</h2>
  <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mb-4">For example, consider two centrifuge bowls rotating at the same speed, say 5,000 RPM. One bowl has a radius of 5 cm, while the other has a radius of 25 cm.</p>
  <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mb-4">Based on the formula, the RCF for the first bowl is 1,400 g-force. However, for the same RPM, the RCF generated by the second (larger) bowl is 7,000 g-force!</p>
  <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mb-4">The centrifuge's separation efficiency with the 7,000g RCF will be much higher than that of the centrifuge with the 1,400g RCF.</p>
  <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mb-6">Therefore, if the user selected the centrifuge solely based on RPM, they would make the wrong choice based on centrifuge effectiveness.</p>

  <!-- Formula -->
  <h2 id="rcf-formula" class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold font-heading text-navy mb-4">Formula to Calculate RCF from RPM</h2>
  <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mb-4">The following formula calculates a centrifuge's Relative Centrifugal Force (RCF) based on the RPM and Centrifuge Bowl Radius. The diagram also illustrates the two terms, namely RPM and bowl radius (r), in the context of the centrifuge bowl.</p>

  <figure class="mb-6">
    <img
      src="/images/centrifuge-rcf-rpm-difference-calculation/centrifuge-bowl-RCF-RPM-formula-1000.webp"
      alt="RCF and RPM Difference & Formula"
      width="1000"
      height="400"
      loading="lazy"
      class="img-cap-800"
    />
    <figcaption class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-2 text-center"><strong>RCF and RPM Difference &amp; Formula</strong></figcaption>
  </figure>

  <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mb-6">RCF&nbsp;=&nbsp;1.118 &times; r &times; n<sup>2</sup> &times; 10<sup>-5</sup></p>

  <!-- Live RCF Calculator -->
  <h2 id="rcf-calculator" class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold font-heading text-navy mb-4">Live RCF Calculator</h2>
  <p class="text-text-light mb-4">Enter your centrifuge bowl radius and speed to instantly calculate RCF (g-force).</p>

  <div class="not-prose my-6 bg-white rounded-2xl border border-gray-200 shadow-md overflow-hidden">
    <!-- Calculator header -->
    <div class="bg-navy px-6 py-4 flex items-center gap-3">
      <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-gold flex-shrink-0" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
        <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M9 7h6m0 10v-3m-3 3h.01M9 17h.01M9 11h.01M12 11h.01M15 11h.01M4 5a2 2 0 012-2h12a2 2 0 012 2v14a2 2 0 01-2 2H6a2 2 0 01-2-2V5z" />
      </svg>
      <h3 class="text-white font-bold font-heading text-base">Centrifuge RCF Calculator</h3>
      <span class="ml-auto text-xs text-gold/70 font-mono">dolphincentrifuge.com</span>
    </div>

    <!-- Inputs -->
    <div class="p-6 grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-5">
      <div>
        <label for="rcf-bowl-radius" class="block text-xs font-semibold text-navy uppercase tracking-wide mb-1">Bowl Radius (inches)</label>
        <input id="rcf-bowl-radius" type="number" value="8" min="1" max="40" step="0.5"
          class="w-full border border-gray-200 rounded-lg px-3 py-2 text-navy font-mono text-base focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-gold/50 focus:border-gold"
          oninput="calcRCF()" />
        <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">Typical disc stack: 4-12 in; decanter: 6-20 in</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <label for="rcf-speed" class="block text-xs font-semibold text-navy uppercase tracking-wide mb-1">Bowl Speed (RPM)</label>
        <input id="rcf-speed" type="number" value="6000" min="100" max="20000" step="100"
          class="w-full border border-gray-200 rounded-lg px-3 py-2 text-navy font-mono text-base focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-gold/50 focus:border-gold"
          oninput="calcRCF()" />
        <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 mt-1">Typical disc stack: 4,000-8,000 RPM</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Result -->
    <div class="mx-6 mb-6 rounded-xl bg-navy/5 border border-navy/10 px-6 py-5 flex flex-col md:flex-row items-center gap-4">
      <div class="flex-1">
        <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wide font-semibold">RCF Formula</p>
        <p class="font-mono text-gray-500 text-sm mt-1">2.840 &times; 10<sup>-5</sup> &times; <span id="rcf-display-radius">8</span> &times; <span id="rcf-display-rpm">6,000</span><sup>2</sup></p>
      </div>
      <div class="text-center">
        <p id="rcf-result" class="text-5xl font-bold font-mono text-gold leading-none">8,179</p>
        <p class="text-xs text-navy font-semibold mt-1 uppercase tracking-wide">&times;g (RCF)</p>
      </div>
      <div class="flex-1 text-right">
        <div id="rcf-status" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-full px-3 py-1 text-xs font-semibold bg-amber-100 text-amber-700">
          <span class="w-2 h-2 rounded-full bg-amber-500 inline-block"></span>
          <span>High Performance</span>
        </div>
        <p id="rcf-guidance" class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-1 max-w-[200px] ml-auto">HFO, beverage clarification, coolant fine solids.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="text-xs text-gray-400 text-center pb-4">&copy; Dolphin Centrifuge - reference only. Contact engineers for application-specific RCF requirements.</p>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
  function calcRCF() {
    const radiusInput = document.getElementById('rcf-bowl-radius');
    const speedInput = document.getElementById('rcf-speed');
    const r = Math.max(parseFloat(radiusInput.value) || 0, 0);
    const n = Math.max(parseFloat(speedInput.value) || 0, 0);
    // Radius entered in inches. Convert to cm: r_cm = r_in x 2.54
    // RCF = 1.118e-5 * r_cm * n^2 = 1.118e-5 * 2.54 * r_in * n^2 = 2.840e-5 * r_in * n^2
    const rcf = 2.840e-5 * r * n * n;
    const result = document.getElementById('rcf-result');
    const status = document.getElementById('rcf-status');
    const guidance = document.getElementById('rcf-guidance');
    const dispR = document.getElementById('rcf-display-radius');
    const dispN = document.getElementById('rcf-display-rpm');

    radiusInput.value = r || '';
    speedInput.value = n || '';
    dispR.textContent = r;
    dispN.textContent = n.toLocaleString();
    result.textContent = Math.round(rcf).toLocaleString();

    if (rcf < 2000) {
      status.className = 'inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-full px-3 py-1 text-xs font-semibold bg-gray-100 text-gray-600';
      status.innerHTML = '<span class="w-2 h-2 rounded-full bg-gray-400 inline-block"></span><span>Low - Basic Separation</span>';
      guidance.textContent = 'Suitable only for coarse solids settlement.';
    } else if (rcf < 4000) {
      status.className = 'inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-full px-3 py-1 text-xs font-semibold bg-blue-100 text-blue-700';
      status.innerHTML = '<span class="w-2 h-2 rounded-full bg-blue-500 inline-block"></span><span>Decanter Range</span>';
      guidance.textContent = 'Typical decanter centrifuge range (2,000-4,000 xg).';
    } else if (rcf < 7000) {
      status.className = 'inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-full px-3 py-1 text-xs font-semibold bg-green-100 text-green-700';
      status.innerHTML = '<span class="w-2 h-2 rounded-full bg-green-500 inline-block"></span><span>Disc Stack Range</span>';
      guidance.textContent = 'Suitable for lube oil & light fuel oil purification.';
    } else if (rcf < 10000) {
      status.className = 'inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-full px-3 py-1 text-xs font-semibold bg-amber-100 text-amber-700';
      status.innerHTML = '<span class="w-2 h-2 rounded-full bg-amber-500 inline-block"></span><span>High Performance</span>';
      guidance.textContent = 'HFO, beverage clarification, coolant fine solids.';
    } else {
      status.className = 'inline-flex items-center gap-2 rounded-full px-3 py-1 text-xs font-semibold bg-purple-100 text-purple-700';
      status.innerHTML = '<span class="w-2 h-2 rounded-full bg-purple-500 inline-block"></span><span>Ultra High G-Force</span>';
      guidance.textContent = 'Pharmaceutical, fine particle, sub-micron separation.';
    }
  }
  calcRCF();
  </script>

  <!-- RCF in Disc Stack Centrifuge -->
  <h2 id="rcf-disc-stack" class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold font-heading text-navy mb-4">RCF in Disc Stack Centrifuge</h2>
  <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mb-4">The Relative Centrifugal Force (RCF) is the crucial factor differentiating a <a href="/disc-stack-centrifuge/" class="text-navy font-semibold hover:text-gold transition-colors">disc-stack centrifuge</a> from other types of centrifuges.</p>
  <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mb-4">An Alfa Laval disc centrifuge generates a higher centrifugal force (g-force) than simple open-bowl or <a href="/decanter-centrifuge/" class="text-navy font-semibold hover:text-gold transition-colors">decanter centrifuges</a>. This higher force allows the disc-stack centrifuge to have higher separation efficiency.</p>
  <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mb-10">Therefore, these centrifugal separators can separate much smaller particles than other centrifuges. They can also separate immiscible liquids with small specific gravity differentials due to their high g-force.</p>

  <!-- Summary -->
  <h2 id="summary" class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold font-heading text-navy mb-4">Summary</h2>
  <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mb-4">RCF and RPM are commonly confused and interchanged terms in the centrifuge world. These two terms are significantly different, as explained above.</p>
  <p class="text-text-light leading-relaxed mb-10">For the end-user, the RCF (aka g-force) is a crucial term because it defines the effectiveness of the centrifuge. The RPM is the bowl speed indicator, but the RPM does not convey any useful information for the application or the process.</p>

  <!-- Related Articles -->
  <div class="mt-10">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-navy mb-4">Related Articles</h2>
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
